How to make the protein-coding gene names from the .gtf file.
This script processes the GENCODE GTF annotation file to generate a clean list of protein-coding genes for downstream RNA-seq differential expression analysis. The GTF file was imported using rtracklayer and converted into a dataframe format. Only transcript-level (`type == "transcript"`) annotations were retained, and key annotation fields including `gene_id`, `gene_name`, `gene_type`, and `transcript_id` were extracted. Duplicate transcript entries were removed to generate a non-redundant annotation table.

Subsequently, genes annotated as `protein_coding` were filtered from the complete annotation dataset to retain only biologically relevant coding genes for downstream analyses. Since multiple transcript isoforms may correspond to the same gene, duplicate transcript entries were collapsed by keeping unique `gene_id` values and removing redundant transcript identifiers (`ENST`). The final processed file containing unique protein-coding genes was then exported for use in RNA-seq count filtering and downstream differential expression workflows.
